%description:
TCP_INFO trio, continued: busyTime/rwndLimited (TcpStatusInfo). INET-native
cumulative-time bookkeeping (not a port of Linux's tcpi_busy_time/
tcpi_rwnd_limited chrono state machine) -- see
TcpConnection::enqueueSendCommandData()/processAckInEstabEtc() (busy) and
sendData() (rwnd). sndbuf_limited has no INET analog and is not surfaced
(documented on TcpStatusInfo itself, not asserted here).

Client writes 5000B under a 1000B advertised window (mss=500): cwnd grows
past 1000B in slow start almost immediately, so the peer's window (not
cwnd) becomes the binding constraint for most of the transfer -- a real,
not contrived, rwnd-limited condition.

This is a self-consistency check only, not a ground-truth parity check:
there is no independent oracle in this repository for INET's own busy/
rwnd-limited definitions (unlike the wire-format-anchored tests elsewhere
in this series). It confirms the bookkeeping behaves sanely (both start
at 0, both grow, rwndLimited never exceeds busyTime since rwnd-limited
periods are by definition a subset of busy time) and stays internally
consistent across a real run -- not that the specific numbers match any
independent reference.

Falsification: none needed as a separate run -- the ordering assertions
below (busyTime and rwndLimited both 0 before any data is sent; both
strictly positive, and rwndLimited < busyTime, once the transfer is well
underway) are themselves the falsification of "the counters don't move"
or "rwndLimited counts something unrelated to busyTime".

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

network = inet.test.moduletest.lib.TcpTestNet1

sim-time-limit = 10s

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false
cmdenv-log-prefix="[%c]: "

*.testing=false

*.tcptester.script=""

*.cli_app.active=true
*.cli_app.localAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.cli_app.localPort=1000
*.cli_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.cli_app.connectPort=2000
*.cli_app.tOpen=0s
*.cli_app.tSend=1s
*.cli_app.sendBytes=5000B
*.cli_app.sendScript=""
*.cli_app.tClose=-1s
*.cli_app.statusRequestScript="0.5,1.5"

*.srv_app.active=false
*.srv_app.localAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.srv_app.localPort=2000
*.srv_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.srv_app.connectPort=1000
*.srv_app.tOpen=0s
*.srv_app.tSend=-1s
*.srv_app.sendBytes=0B
*.srv_app.sendScript=""
*.srv_app.tClose=-1s

*.*_tcp.advertisedWindow = 1000
*.*_tcp.delayedAcksEnabled = false
*.*_tcp.nagleEnabled = false
*.*_tcp.sackSupport = false
*.*_tcp.windowScalingSupport = false
*.*_tcp.timestampSupport = false
*.*_tcp.mss = 500
*.*_tcp.tcpAlgorithmClass = "TcpReno"

include ../../lib/tcp-legacy.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# t=0.5: idle baseline, before tSend -- both counters still exactly 0.
%contains: stdout
STATUS: caState=0 backoff=0 lost=4294967295 probes=0 bytesReceived=0 deliveredCePkts=0 deliveredCeBytes=0 busyTime=0 rwndLimited=0
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# t=1.5: 0.5s into the transfer, both counters have grown, and rwndLimited stays
%# below busyTime (window-limited time is a subset of overall busy time).
%contains: stdout
busyTime=0.024 rwndLimited=0.012
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
